definition.value: A lysophosphatidylcholine 16:0 in which a hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) group is attached to the glycero moiety at position 1.

A phosphatidylcholine 32:0 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl). A synthetic phospholipid used in liposomes and lipid bilayers to study biological membranes. It is also a major constituent of pulmonary surfactants.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:0 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and octadecanoyl (stearoyl) respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:1 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 9Z-octadecenoyl (oleoyl) respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:2 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 9Z,12Z-octadecadienoyl (linoleoyl) respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:4 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z-eicosatetraenoyl (arachidonoyl) respectively.
A lysophosphatidylethanolamine zwitterion 16:0 obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1-hexadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 32:0 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1,2-dihexadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 34:1 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1-hexadecanoyl-2-octadecanoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 34:1 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1-hexadecanoyl-2-(9Z-octadecenoyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 34:2 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1-hexadecanoyl-2-(9Z,12Z-octadecadienoyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.

A phosphatidylethanolamine 36:4 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of 1-hexadecanoyl-2-(5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z-eicosatetraenoyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
A tetrapeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-D-phenylalanine, beta-alanine, L-histidine and D-prolinamide residues coupled in sequence.
A sesquiterpene lactone based on germacrane skeleton.
A pyridinecarbaldehyde that is pyridine in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by a formyl group.
A pentapeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-L-glutamine, D-phenylalanine, L-histidine, D-proline and beta-alanine residues coupled in sequence.
An oligopeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-L-glutamine, D-phenylalanine, L-histidine, D-proline and two beta-alanine residues coupled in sequence.
A tripeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-D-phenylalanine, L-histidine and D-proline residues coupled in sequence.
A tripeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-D-phenylalanine, L-histidine and D-prolinamide residues coupled in sequence.
An O-acylcarnitine having isobutyryl as the acyl substituent.
An N-acylglycine that is glycine with an amine hydrogen substituted by a 2-methylbut-2-enoyl (tiglyl) group.
A tripeptide comprising N(2)-acetyl-D-glutamic acid, L-histidine and D-prolinamide residues coupled in sequence.
A dipeptide that is the N-(N(alpha)-acetyl-D-histidyl) derivative of L-proline.
A dipeptide that is the N(1)-(N(alpha)-acetyl-L-histidyl) derivative of D-prolinamide.
A dipeptide that is the N(1)-(N(alpha)-acetyl-L-histidyl) derivative of D-proline.
An O-acylcarnitine having acetyl as the acyl substituent.
A C5-acylcarnitine having isovaleryl as the acyl substituent.
A C5-acylcarnitine having 2-methylbutyryl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having 3-hydroxyisovaleryl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having malonyl as the acyl substituent.
A member of the class of ptercoarpans that is cis-pterocarpan  substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3 and a methylenedioxy group across positions 8 and 9.
The (+)-enantiomer of maackiain.
An O-acylcarnitine having methylmalonyl as the acyl substituent.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole which is substituted at positions 1, 3, and 5 by 4-sulfamoylphenyl, difluoromethyl and 3-fluoro-4-methoxyphenyl groups, respectively. A selective cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor, it is used in veterinary medicine for the control of pain and inflammation associated with osteoarthritis in dogs.
The simplest member of the class of pterocarpans that is 6a,11a-dihydro-6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene.
An O-acylcarnitine having succinyl as the acyl substituent.
A pterocarpan in which the ring junction between 1-benzofuran and chromene rings has a cis stereochemistry.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoheptanedioic acid.
An O-acylcarnitine having (2E)-octenoyl as the acyl substituent.
An N-acylsulfonamide resulting from the formal condensation of valdecoxib with propionic acid. It is a prodrug for valdecoxib.
An O-acylcarnitine having octanoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having glutaryl as the acyl substituent.
A member of the class of 1,3-oxazoles that is that is 1,3-oxazole which is substituted at positions 2, 4 and 5 by methyl, cyclohexyl, and 3-fluoro-4-sulfamoylphenyl groups, respectively.
An O-acylcarnitine having (2E)-hexenedioyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having 3-hydroxy-cis-5-octenoyl as the acyl substituent.

An amino acid that is phenylacetic acid which is substituted at position 2 by the nitrogen of 2-chloro-6-fluoroaniline and at position 5 by a methyl group. A highly selective cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor, it was briefly used for the treatment of osteoarthritis, but was withdrawn due to concersns of hepatotoxicity.
An O-acylcarnitine having (2E,5Z,7E)-decatrienoyl as the acyl substituent.
